div.p: Randomized controlled trials minimize biasing factors within a study's design but external factors may still introduce bias into research. “Positive Publication Bias” has been described as the preference of journals, and authors, to publish positive results which are more likely to be cited1. "Funding Bias" has been investigated in diseases outside of Alzheimer's where authors found industry funded studies tended to favor pharmacologic treatment group outcomes2. The point at which funding bias is introduced varies and can manifest as altered trial design, early termination of trials, and restriction of publication rights3.
Both of these sources of bias have the potential to create an overly positive view of treatment effects which may influence patient care outside of a trial setting.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; width: 318px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal; text-align: center;

div.div: Literature Selection: Human randomized controlled trials on Alzheimer's Disease were identified through PubMed and limited according to the inclusion criteria of:

ol.li: Published in the top 5 journals ranked by publication count in the investigated years
Reported raw baseline and post-treatment values for at last one efficacy measure

div.div: Analysis: 150 studies were aggregated and analyzed to produce two main measures of effect size.

ol.li: The standardized mean difference was calculated as the MedAware Standardized Index of Treatment Effect (MSI-E) for outcomes with an identifiable directionality.
The absolute value of the MSI-E (|MSI-E|) was calculated for all efficacy measures as a measure of overall effect size.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; width: 318px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal; text-align: center;

ul.li: No significant difference is seen in the MSI-E between funding sources as a whole (Fig. 1a).
Absolute effect sizes, |MSI-E| are much larger in the Control Groups of Foundation/Non-Profit funded studies compared to all other groups (Fig. 1b).
Publishing journal is significantly related to the directional effect sizes, MSI-E, in both Treatment and Control groups (Fig. 2a).
The absolute effect sizes of Control groups among the journals differs but the trend does not extend to Treatment Groups (Fig. 2b).

li.span: Both directional and absolute effect sizes are significantly different depending on an author's primary affiliation (Fig. 3).
Medical Facility affiliated authors reported more positive outcomes when compared to Pharmaceutical and University authored Treatment Groups (Fig. 3a, p < .0001).
Absolute effect sizes in Control Groups were smaller when reported by authors from Medical Facilities (Fig. 3b).

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; width: 318px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal; text-align: center;

div.span: Controlling for external research biases is necessary to ensure reviews and meta-analyses of patient outcomes align with the true effects of treatments. Ignoring the differences that exist among factors such as Funding Source, Publishing Journal, and Author Affiliations may skew results in a way that impacts patients in the future.

Identifying the cause of external biases is not possible by looking at the results alone but this investigation suggests several potential entry points of bias that can be accounted for in future research. To minimize the influence of external factors, authors should strive for a diverse study set with respect to Funding Source, Journals, and Authors.

div.font:
Funding Institution: Any institution providing monetary contributions to the primary author of the study.
Publishing Journal: The journal in which the included article was published.
Author Affiliation: The primary institution listed for the first author of the trial.
